      id: 61
      max: 4/1
      obj: Define `class Dog:` with `__init__(self, name):` storing `self.name = name`.
      expl: '`__init__` runs automatically when an object is created.'
      sol: "class Dog:\n    def __init__(self, name):\n        self.name = name"
      start: ''
    - name: Read an Attribute
      hint: Use `dog.name`.
      tests:
      - exp: 'Rex

          '
      id: 62
      max: 3/1
      obj: Create `Dog("Rex")` and print its `name` attribute.
      expl: Attributes store information inside objects.
      sol: "dog = Dog(\"Rex\")\n              print(dog.name)"
      start: "class Dog:\n                  def __init__(self, name):\n                      self.name = name\n\n        \
        \      "
    - name: Class Methods
      hint: Methods belong inside a class.
      tests:
      - exp: 'Woof!

          '
      id: 63
      max: 8/1
      obj: Add method `bark(self)` to `Dog` that prints `"Woof!"`. Create `Dog("Rex")` and call `bark()`.
      expl: Methods are functions defined inside classes.
      sol: "class Dog:\n                  def __init__(self, name):\n                      self.name = name\n\n          \
        \        def bark(self):\n                      print(\"Woof!\")\n\n              dog = Dog(\"Rex\")\n           \
        \   dog.bark()"
      start: ''
    - name: Attribute Methods
      hint: Use an f-string.
      tests:
      - exp: 'Rex says Woof!

          '
      id: 64
      max: 8/1
      obj: Modify `bark()` so it prints `"Rex says Woof!"` using `self.name`.
      expl: Methods can access instance attributes through `self`.
      sol: "class Dog:\n                  def __init__(self, name):\n                      self.name = name\n\n          \
        \        def bark(self):\n                      print(f\"{self.name} says Woof!\")\n\n              dog = Dog(\"Rex\"\
        )\n              dog.bark()"
      start: ''
    - name: Inheritance
      hint: Subclass syntax uses parentheses.
      sourceChecks:
        classes:
        - Puppy
        inheritance:
          Puppy:
          - Dog
      id: 65
      max: 3/1
      obj: Define `class Puppy(Dog):` that inherits from `Dog`.
      expl: Inheritance lets one class reuse another class's behavior.
      sol: "class Puppy(Dog):\n    pass"
      start: "class Dog:\n    pass\n"
    - name: Override a Method
      hint: Create a new method with the same name.
      tests:
      - exp: 'Yip!

          '
      id: 66
      max: 6/1
      obj: Override `bark()` inside `Puppy` so it prints `"Yip!"`.
      expl: Child classes can replace inherited behavior.
      sol: "class Puppy(Dog):\n                  def bark(self):\n                      print(\"Yip!\")\n\n              p\
        \ = Puppy()\n              p.bark()"
      start: "class Dog:\n                  def bark(self):\n                      print(\"Woof!\")\n\n              "
    - name: Pet Simulator
      example:
        input: []
        output: '50

          True

          '
      tests:
      - exp: '50

          True

          '
      id: 67
      max: 14/1
      obj: Create a class `Character` with `__init__(self, name, health)` storing both attributes, method `take_damage(amount)`
        that reduces health, and method `is_alive()` that returns `self.health > 0`. Create a character with 100 health, apply
        30 then 20 damage, and print health and alive status.
      sol: "class Character:\n                  def __init__(self, name, health):\n                      self.name = name\n\
        \                      self.health = health\n\n                  def take_damage(self, amount):\n                \
        \      self.health -= amount\n\n                  def is_alive(self):\n                      return self.health >\
        \ 0\n\n              hero = Character(\"Hero\", 100)\n              hero.take_damage(30)\n              hero.take_damage(20)\n\
        \              print(hero.health)\n              print(hero.is_alive())"
      start: ''
